### **2. Two people get on the same lift on the ground floor. First person goes to 10/F and second person goes to 30/F. How long does it take?**

We assume the elevator travels upwards, stopping at 10/F first, then 30/F. The total time is the sum of the travel time to 10/F and the travel time from 10/F to 30/F.

**Leg 1: Ground Floor (0m) to 10/F (50m)**

*   **Distance:** $10 \text{ floors} \times 5 \text{ m/floor} = 50 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Acceleration/Deceleration Distance:** $12.5 \text{ m} + 12.5 \text{ m} = 25 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Check:** Since $25 \text{ m} < 50 \text{ m}$, the elevator reaches max speed.
*   **Cruise Distance:** $50 - 25 = 25 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Cruise Time:** $\frac{25}{5} = 5 \text{ seconds}$.
*   **Total Time Leg 1:** $5 \text{ (accel)} + 5 \text{ (cruise)} + 5 \text{ (decel)} = 15 \text{ seconds}$.

**Leg 2: 10/F (50m) to 30/F (150m)**

*   **Distance:** $150 - 50 = 100 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Acceleration/Deceleration Distance:** $25 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Check:** Since $25 \text{ m} < 100 \text{ m}$, the elevator reaches max speed.
*   **Cruise Distance:** $100 - 25 = 75 \text{ meters}$.
*   **Cruise Time:** $\frac{75}{5} = 15 \text{ seconds}$.
*   **Total Time Leg 2:** $5 \text{ (accel)} + 15 \text{ (cruise)} + 5 \text{ (decel)} = 25 \text{ seconds}$.

**Total Time:**
$$t_{total} = 15 + 25 = 40 \text{ seconds}$$

**Answer:** It takes **40 seconds** for the second person to reach the 30th floor (and 15 seconds for the first person to reach the 10th floor).

